# of the module follows symlinks. But module.rules matching might still use
# the original path. There's a separate setting: module.rules[].resolve.symlinks
#
# Actually, there's a config option resolve.symlinks that affects module resolution,
# and there are also per-rule resolve settings. But the key question is what 
# path webpack uses for the Rule.include test.
#
# Looking at webpack source code, the resource path used for rule matching is
# the one AFTER resolution but it depends on the resolve.symlinks setting.
# If symlinks are resolved, the real path is used. If not, the symlinked path.
#
# The default is resolve.symlinks: true, so real paths should be used.
# BUT - for yarn workspaces, the symlinks in node_modules are created by yarn.
# webpack's resolve.symlinks follows these symlinks during RESOLUTION.
# However, the resulting resource path might still be the node_modules path
# if webpack uses the initial path rather than the resolved real path for 
# rule matching.
#
# In webpack 5, there was a change where resolve.symlinks affects whether
# the realpath or the symlink path is used for rule matching.
# See: https://webpack.js.org/configuration/resolve/#resolvesymlinks
# "When enabled, symlinked resources are resolved to their real path"
# This affects RESOLUTION. For rule matching, webpack uses the resource path
# which is the resolved path.
#
